explanation:
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro): The assignment impl = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(...) is the direct source of any hidden calls or comparisons; the macro body may call helper functions or perform comparisons (e.g., of token fields). Inspecting this macro is needed to see if it expands to code that uses memcmp on strings.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: The static call graph and common implementations map tokens to table indices in this helper. If OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET or related code calls this function, it (or other index helpers) is a likely place memcmp could be used to compare token/string fields; analyzing it is required to detect memcmp-based string comparisons.
- OS_impl_condvar_table: The table symbol and its element type are needed to understand how lookup is performed (what fields are compared, types of keys). The table layout can indicate whether string comparisons occur during lookup.
- OS_object_token_t (type definition): The token contents determine what is being compared (IDs, names, or strings). To decide if memcmp is being used to compare null-terminated strings you must know the token fields and whether they are NUL-terminated strings.
- OS_impl_condvar_internal_record_t (type/struct): The record type (and its fields such as any name/member used in comparisons) helps determine whether comparisons involve null-terminated strings and therefore whether memcmp would be inappropriate.
- memcmp (standard library): Include the memcmp symbol/usage so the analyzer can detect direct uses. If memcmp appears in any of the above implementations, the analyzer must check how it is used (with explicit lengths vs. on NUL-terminated strings) to determine MISRA compliance.
